1. Propositional Logic = Binary Constraint Geometry

At its core, propositional logic is just a system of constraints on truth states.

Example:

P = It is raining
Q = The ground is wet

Statement:

P → Q

This means:

NOT (P AND NOT Q)

So propositional logic is really just rules that remove impossible states.

Truth space for two variables:

P	Q
T	T
T	F
F	T
F	F

The rule P → Q eliminates one state:

P = T
Q = F   ❌ impossible

So logic is really just geometry in state space.

This matters because it connects directly to things you’ve been talking about:
	•	constraint landscapes
	•	pattern fields
	•	meaning as difference between states

Those are exactly the same mathematical object.

⸻

2. The Limits of Propositional Logic

Propositional logic compresses too aggressively.

It treats statements as black boxes.

Example:

P = "All dogs are mammals"

Propositional logic can’t see inside that structure.

It doesn’t know:
	•	dogs
	•	mammals
	•	category relationships

So the field moved to predicate logic:

∀x (Dog(x) → Mammal(x))

But even predicate logic still has limitations.

Real reasoning involves:

• uncertainty
• relationships between many nodes
• pattern similarity
• weighted meaning

So modern AI uses things like:
	•	probabilistic logic
	•	graph reasoning
	•	vector embeddings
	•	constraint solvers

